TWO SUM II – INPUT ARRAY IS SORTED
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Given a 1-indexed array numbers sorted in non-decreasing order,
find two numbers such that they add up to a specific target.

Return the indices (1-based) of the two numbers as:
[index1, index2]

Constraints:
• Exactly one solution exists
• Cannot use the same element twice
• Must use O(1) extra space


Example 1:
Input:  numbers = [2,7,11,15], target = 9
Output: [1,2]

Example 2:
Input:  numbers = [2,3,4], target = 6
Output: [1,3]

Example 3:
Input:  numbers = [-1,0], target = -1
Output: [1,2]


APPROACH – TWO POINTER
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Start pointer at beginning
• End pointer at last index
• If sum == target → return indices
• If sum < target → move start forward
• If sum > target → move end backward
• Time Complexity: O(n)
• Space Complexity: O(1)


class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& numbers, int target) 
    {
        int start = 0;
        int end = numbers.size() - 1;

        while (start < end)
        {
            int sum = numbers[start] + numbers[end];

            if (sum == target)
            {
                return {start + 1, end + 1};   // 1-based index
            }
            else if (sum < target)
            {
                start++;
            }
            else
            {
                end--;
            }
        }

        return {};
    }
};
